of allegory as a symbolic mode, shows how it expresses fundamental emotional and cognitive drives, and relates it to a wide variety of aesthetic devices. Revealing the immense richness of the allegorical tradition, the book demonstrates how allegory works in literature and art, as well as everyday speech, sales pitches, and religious and political appeals.In his new afterword, Fletcher documents the rise of a disturbing new type of allegory--allegory without ideas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aAbbot Suger.  aAbraham, Karl.  aAeneas.  aAristophanes.  aBalakian, Anna.  aBeerbohm, Max.  aBernard Sylvestris.  aBoethius.  aCandide.  aCastiglione, Baldassare.  aCharlemagne.  aEcclesiastes.  aFernández, Ramón.  aGoodman, Paul.  aHawthorne, Nathaniel.  aHobbes, Thomas.  aIzutsu, Toshihiko.  aJakobson, Roman.  aKames, Lord.  aKitzinger, Ernst.  aLangland, William.  aLuchins, Abraham and Edith.  aLévy-Bruhl, Lucien.  aManichaeism.  aOedipus Rex.  aParadeigma.  aambivalence.  aandrogyny.  aastral symbolism.  ablason.  acosmogonic ornamentation.  adaemon, etymology.  adecomposition.  adoppelgänger.  aemblema.  aemblems.  aencapsulation.  aepideictic rhetoric.  ageneration of subcharacters.  aiconography and iconology.  ainversion.  amagic.  amagnitude.  amechanic form.  amicrocosmos.  amonumentality.  anaturalism.  aneoplatonic imagery.  anumber symbolism.  aornament.1 aBloom, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, Harold.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400842049zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400842049423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400842049.jpg  aEBA_BACKAL